@node "intr" "Introduction"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Introduction@{fg text}@{uu}

YGM stands for 'You've Got Mail'.
It checks your POP3 mailboxes for new mails so that you do not have to start your favourite yet sometimes bulky mail client just for this. 

YGM shows you how many mails are waiting in your mailboxes for download and their approximate size. 

YGM is also useful for email providers who require a POP3 authentication before you are allowed to send emails over their SMTP servers, a security feature also known as 'SMTP-after-POP'. 



@endnode

@node "reqr" "Requirements"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Requirements@{fg text}@{uu}


@{lindent 2} 
° AmigaOS 2.04 or higher, AmigaOS 3.5 or higher recommended. 
° AmiTCP 4 compatible TCP/IP stack. 
° ReAction classes or fgui.library V1.29 or newer. 
° An Internet connection and at least one mail account with POP3 access. 
@{lindent 0}


@endnode

@node "inst" "Installation"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Installation@{fg text}@{uu}

There is no special installation process necessary to run YGM.
Just unpack the archive to a place you like and run the program. 

However, if you want a more convenient method of installing the program there is an Installer script provided with this release, called Install-YGM.
If you double-click its icon only those files will be installed you really need. 



@endnode

@node "usag" "Usage"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Usage@{fg text}@{uu}

YGM can either be run from the @{" CLI " LINK rcli} or from the @{" Workbench " LINK rwbn}. 

To be able to access the mailbox status from other applications YGM gives back @{" result codes " LINK rslt} and creates an @{" Environment variable " LINK enva}. 

If you run the program from the CLI without displaying its GUI by specifying the NOREQ argument it will try to access all specified mailboxes once and then quit.
If you run it with a GUI you are able to query the POP3 mail servers multiple times. 

@{fg highlight}The GUI@{fg text}

The GUI requester consists of a text gadget which shows the status of the current mailbox being accessed and the three button gadgets @{b}Connect@{ub}, @{b}Skip@{ub} and @{b}Quit@{ub}.
With @{b}Connect@{ub} you start the query process.
With @{b}Quit@{ub} you can either stop a running query process or quit the program when no query process is running.
With @{b}Skip@{ub} you can stop querying the current mailbox and go over to the next one. 

If you run the program with a GUI you can also start the query sequence by sending a @{b}CTRL-F@{ub} signal to the program.
You can quit the program or stop a query process from outside by sending a @{b}CTRL-C@{ub} signal or from the Commodity Exchange program. 

The GUI can be hidden by choosing the menu item 'Project/Hide' or by selecting the window's close gadget.
It can be reopened by double clicking the YGM icon or through Commodity Exchange. 

By default the GUI is opened at the best position relativ to the mouse pointer.
If you prefer to have the GUI opened at a fixed position you can select the menu items 'Window/Snapshot' and 'Window/UnSnapshot'. 

If the query sequence was not successful for a mailbox, the reason for the failure may be given in the text gadget of the GUI requester and/or in the YGM @{" log file " LINK wbtt_logname}. 

@{fg highlight}YGM as a commodity@{fg text}

YGM runs as a Commodity and the behaviour of it can be controlled with the 'Commodities Exchange' program.
Via Commodity Exchange you can hide and reopen the YGM GUI, you can activate and deactivate it and you can quit the program. 



@endnode

@node "rcli" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}


Format:   YGM [@{" USER|USERID " LINK wbtt_ups}] <userid> [@{" PASS|PASSWORD " LINK wbtt_ups}] <password>
          [@{" SERVER " LINK wbtt_ups}] <server>
          [@{" USER2 " LINK wbtt_ups} <userid>] [@{" PASS2 " LINK wbtt_ups} <password>] [@{" SERVER2 " LINK wbtt_ups} <server>]
          [@{" USER3 " LINK wbtt_ups} <userid>] [@{" PASS3 " LINK wbtt_ups} <password>] [@{" SERVER3 " LINK wbtt_ups} <server>]
          [@{" ACCESSFILE " LINK wbtt_accessfile} <accessfile>]
          [@{" NOMAILICON " LINK wbtt_mailicons} <path>] [@{" NEWMAILICON " LINK wbtt_mailicons} <path>] [@{" OLDMAILICON " LINK wbtt_mailicons} <path>]
          [@{" BUSYICON " LINK wbtt_mailicons} <path>] [@{" NODEFICON " LINK wbtt_nodeficon}] [@{" ICONX " LINK wbtt_iconxy} <xpos>] [@{" ICONY " LINK wbtt_iconxy} <ypos>]
          [@{" TIMEOUT " LINK wbtt_timeout} <seconds>]
          [@{" DISPLAYBEEP " LINK wbtt_displaybeep}] [@{" PLAYSOUND " LINK wbtt_playsound} <soundfile>] [@{" RUNCOMMAND " LINK wbtt_runcommand} <command>]
          [@{" AUTOSTART " LINK wbtt_autostart}] [@{" AUTOQUIT " LINK wbtt_autoquit}] [@{" DELAY " LINK wbtt_delay} <ticks>] [@{" REPEAT " LINK wbtt_repeat} <minutes>]
          [@{" NOQUIT " LINK wbtt_noquit}] [@{" QUIT " LINK wbtt_quit}] [@{" NOREQ " LINK wbtt_noreq}] [@{" QUIET " LINK wbtt_quiet}]
          [@{" LOGLEVEL " LINK wbtt_loglevel} <level>] [@{" LOGNAME " LINK wbtt_logname} <logfile>] [@{" NOLOG " LINK wbtt_nolog}]
          [@{" CX_PRIORITY " LINK wbtt_cx_priority} <priority>] [@{" CX_POPUP " LINK wbtt_cx_popup} no] [@{" CX_POPKEY " LINK wbtt_cx_popkey} <key>]
          [@{" GUIENGINE " LINK wbtt_guiengine} fgui]


Template: USER=USERID/K,PASS=PASSWORD/K,SERVER/K,
          USER2/K,PASS2/K,SERVER2/K,USER3/K,PASS3/K,SERVER3/K,ACCESSFILE/K,
          NOMAILICON/K,NEWMAILICON/K,OLDMAILICON/K,
          BUSYICON/K,NODEFICON/S,ICONX/K/N,ICONY/K/N,
          TIMEOUT/K/N,DISPLAYBEEP/S,PLAYSOUND/K,RUNCOMMAND/K,
          AUTOSTART/S,AUTOQUIT/S,DELAY/K/N,REPEAT/K/N,
          NOQUIT/S,QUIT/S,NOREQ/S,QUIET/S,
          LOGLEVEL/K/N,LOGNAME/K,NOLOG/S,
          CX_PRIORITY/K/N,CX_POPUP/K,CX_POPKEY/K,
          GUIENGINE/K


@endnode

@node "wbtt_ups" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}USER, PASS, SERVER
USER2, PASS2, SERVER2
USER3, PASS3, SERVER3
@{ub} 

YGM allows an unlimited number of mailboxes to be queried in a single run.
With USER, USER2 and USER3 you can specify the username of each of the first 3 mail accounts, with PASS, PASS2 and PASS3 you specify the passwords and with SERVER, SERVER2 and SERVER3 the names or IP adresses of the POP3 mail servers.
If you have to use a different port number than the default you can specify it directly after the SERVER argument, using a ':' to separate server name and port number. 

If you want to access more than one mailbox please use the ACCESSFILE argument as USER2/USER3, PASS2/PASS3 and SERVER2/SERVER3 may disappear in future versions. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_accessfile" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}ACCESSFILE@{ub} 

offers a different way to specify all necessary information to access your mailboxes and it allows to query an unlimited number of boxes in a single run.


With this argument you have to specify the path and name of a file which contains usernames, passwords and server names.
In addition to that three more fields, 'alias', 'disable' and 'apop' may be entered:
With 'alias' a different name for 'username' can be specified whenever it is displayed or written to the logfile.
Specifying 'disable' tells YGM to skip checking the box of the very line.
When 'apop' is set username and password will be transmitted more safely using the APOP command.
Without APOP both username and password will be transitted in the clear over the net.
Note that not all mail servers support APOP. 

For 'disable' and 'apop' the values 'Y' for yes and 'N' for no are allowed. 

Each line of the file should have the following format:


   @{i}username@{ui},@{i}password@{ui},@{i}server@{ui}[:@{i}port@{ui}][,@{i}alias@{ui}[,@{i}disable@{ui}[,@{i}apop@{ui}]]]


Comments in the access file are identified by a '#' character, blank lines, blanks and tabs are ignored. 

@{b}Example:@{ub}

   JohnDoe,   mysecret,  my.server.com                  # John's-Account
   JaneDoe,   hersecret, her.server.com:147, JD,   Y    # Jane's-Account
   JoanneDoe, hersecret, her.server.com,     JoJo, Y, Y # Joanne's-Account


An example version of an access file called YGM.dat can also be found in the 's' drawer of this release. 

If you specify mailbox information by direct arguments (USER, PASS, SERVER, etc.) @{b}and@{ub} ACCESSFILE, the mailboxes specified with ACCESSFILE will be queried @{b}after@{ub} those given with direct arguments. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_mailicons" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}NOMAILICON
NEWMAILICON
OLDMAILICON
BUSYICON
@{ub} 

By default YGM displays an application icon on the Workbench to visualize the current mailbox status using the standard YGM.info file. 

With NOMAILICON, NEWMAILICON, OLDMAILICON and BUSYICON you can specify different icons for cases when there is no, new or old mail in your mailboxes and when YGM is busy to query the mail server.
You have to specify the complete path of the icon to use, without the '.info' extension. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_nodeficon" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}NODEFICON@{ub} 

tells YGM not to display a default application icon.
Only application icons specified via NOMAILICON, NEWMAILICON, OLDMAILICON and BUSYICON will be created. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_iconxy" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}ICONX
ICONY
@{ub} 

By default YGM displays its application icon at no specific position on the Workbench.
If you want it to appear at a fixed position you can specify the desired horizontal and vertical position via ICONX and ICONY. 

When YGM is running under OS3.5 you can use a more convenient method having the icon displayed at a specific position by selecting the Workbench menu items 'Icons/Snapshot' and 'Icons/UnSnapshot'. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_timeout" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}TIMEOUT@{ub} 

With TIMEOUT you can specify the maximum length of the period in seconds YGM tries to connect to each mail server before it will fail.
The default for TIMEOUT is 30. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_displaybeep" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}DISPLAYBEEP@{ub} 

If this argument is specified, YGM flashes all screens if at least one mailbox being queried has new mail. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_playsound" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}PLAYSOUND@{ub} 

With this argument you have to specify the path and name of a soundfile which will be played if at least one mailbox being queried has new mail.
The soundfile can be an 8svx file for example. 

Please note that YGM needs the datatypes.library to use this feature so you must have at least OS 3.0 installed to use it successfully. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_runcommand" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}RUNCOMMAND@{ub} 

With this argument you have to specify the path and name of a program or script which will be run automatically if at least one mailbox being queried has new mail.
This program can be your favourite mailer for example. 

The program or script will be startet asynchronously so you don't have to use the 'run' command. 

To run a program you could specify


   RUNCOMMAND="YAM:YAM"

to run YAM when you've got new mail. 

To execute an ARexx script you could use


   RUNCOMMAND="sys:rexxc/rx rexx/havemail.rexx"


If you want to have access to the current mail status from the program or script being started you can examine the environment variable @{" YGMBOXSTAT " LINK enva}. 

If you specified RUNCOMMAND and you have at least one mail box with mail waiting, either new or old mail, the menu item 'Mailbox/Execute RUNCOMMAND' becomes selectable.
This allows to execute the RUNCOMMAND when YGM already checked the mails before. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_autostart" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}AUTOSTART@{ub} 

With AUTOSTART the connect procedure begins shortly after the YGM requester shows up. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_autoquit" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}AUTOQUIT@{ub} 

With AUTOQUIT the program quits after all mailboxes have been processed.
Note that AUTOQUIT will only be effective if AUTOSTART is also set. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_delay" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}DELAY@{ub} 

expects a ticks-per-second value (with 50 ticks per second) which will be used as a delay after updating the information display of the YGM requester.
If you have an ISP with a large bandwidth it might be necessary to wait some time so that you can read all messages.  If it's a slow connection, you should specify 0.
The default for DELAY is 0. 

AUTOSTART, AUTOQUIT and DELAY are only significant if you run YGM with a GUI, which means, you do not specify NOREQ. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_repeat" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}REPEAT@{ub} 

With REPEAT you can tell YGM to check your mail accounts every time the specified interval has elapsed.
Values above 0 are interpreted as minutes, values below 0 as seconds.
The default for REPEAT is 0. 

When YGM is set to 'Inactive' through Commodity Exchange the repeat function will be suspended until it is set to 'Active' again. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_noquit" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}NOQUIT@{ub} 

The default behaviour of YGM is to quit if it's already running and beeing started again.
By specifying NOQUIT you tell YGM not to quit in this case.
This way you can call YGM repeatedly from a script without the need to check first if it is already running or not. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_quit" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}QUIT@{ub} 

By specifying QUIT you tell an already running instance of YGM to quit.




@endnode

@node "wbtt_noreq" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}NOREQ@{ub} 

Specifying NOREQ prevents YGM from showing a GUI.
The program will check all specified mailboxes once and then exits. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_quiet" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}QUIET@{ub} 

With QUIET you prevent YGM from printing informative and diagnostic messages to the console if it was started from the CLI. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_loglevel" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}LOGLEVEL@{ub} 

With this argument you can adjust the amount of information which will be written to the YGM logfile. 

The following values may be given: 


    0 - Do not write any messages
    1 - Only write error messages
    2 - Write any available messages


The default for LOGLEVEL is 2. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_logname" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}LOGNAME@{ub} 

By default YGM writes informative and diagnostic messages to the file @{b}T:YGM.log@{ub}.
With this argument you can determine a different path and file name for the log messages. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_nolog" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}NOLOG@{ub} 

This argument prevents YGM from writing any log messages.
It has the same effect as LOGLEVEL=0. 

Please use LOGLEVEL=0 as this argument may disappear in future versions. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_cx_priority" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub} 

allows to set the priority of YGM in relation to all other running Commodities.
It accepts values from -128 to 127, the higher the number, the higher the priority of the YGM commodity.
By default a priority of 0 is used. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_cx_popup" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}CX_POPUP@{ub} 

By default YGM opens a GUI (unless NOREQ is specified).
With CX_POPUP=NO YGM will start in hidden state allowing to open the GUI later by double clicking its icon or through the Commodity program Exchange. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_cx_popkey" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub} 

Another way to reopen a hidden GUI is by specifying a hot key for YGM via CX_POPKEY and pressing this key. 



@endnode

@node "wbtt_guiengine" "Running from the CLI"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the CLI@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}GUIENGINE@{ub} 

By default YGM tries to create its GUI by using the ReAction layout engine.
If the ReAction engine can not be opened for some reason the proprietary GUI engine fgui.library will be used.
However, if you prefer to use fgui.library even if ReAction is available you can do so by specifying GUIENGINE=FGUI. 



@endnode

@node "rslt" "Result codes"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Result codes@{fg text}@{uu}

If you run the program from the CLI you can examine the result codes RC and RESULT2 to see which mailbox has mail waiting after the program has been quit. 

If all mailboxes were queried successfully and there is no mail in any one of them the program gives back a return code (RC) of 0. 

A return code of 1 indicates that no error occurred and at least one mailbox has got mail.
In this case RESULT2 will contain the mail status of each mailbox as a bit mask where bit 1 represents the first, bit 2 represents the second and bit 3 represents the third mailbox.
If a bit is set it means this mailbox has got new mail, so a RESULT2 of 5 means mailbox 1 and 3 have mail.
This scheme works for the first 16 mailboxes being specified. 

To access the current mailbox status while YGM is running the environment variable @{" YGMBOXSTAT " LINK enva} can be examined. 

All other return codes mean that there was an error while accessing one or all mailboxes.  A return code of 10 ususally means that a DOS error occurred.  In this case the DOS error code will be returned in RESULT2 and the error text will be printed to the console.
A return code of 20 means that something serious prevented the program from running, e.g. a library couldn't be opened.
This return code will also be given back if a TCP/IP error occurred or the mail server didn't like a username or password.  In case of a TCP/IP error a TCP/IP error code will be returned in RESULT2. 



@endnode

@node "enva" "Environment variable"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Environment variable@{fg text}@{uu}

After each query sequence YGM stores the current mailbox status in the environment variable YGMBOXSTAT.
It has the same bitmask format as the @{" RESULT2 " LINK rslt} return code. 



@endnode

@node "rwbn" "Running from the Workbench"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Running from the Workbench@{fg text}@{uu}

All of the @{" CLI " LINK rcli} arguments except NOREQ and QUIET also exist as Workbench ToolTypes with the same meaning. 



@endnode

@node "note" "Security Notes"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Security Notes@{fg text}@{uu}

A note on security:
Please be aware of the fact that the usernames and passwords you specify will be used to access your mailboxes.
Especially your passwords should always be kept secret so that no one else but you has access to your mail accounts.
If you run YGM from the Workbench, usernames and passwords are only stored in one place by default:  as ToolTypes in the YGM icon, which equals to the file YGM.info.
They are @{u}@{b}NOT@{ub} encrypted@{uu} so make sure that nobody else but you has access to this file!
If you run the program from the CLI you normally specify usernames and passwords as command line arguments so they are not stored anywhere.
However, if you run YGM from a script file, it is possible to store usernames and passwords unencrypted, so, as above:  make sure that no-one else but you has access to this script!
If you use the ACCESSFILE argument, all information in the file specified should be kept secret too! 

I can guarantee you that YGM does nothing naughty with your usernames/passwords like installing a trojan horse or things like that.
However, you as the enduser should make sure that you are not using a cracked version which might behave very bad. 

In order to give you the possibility to verify that this archive has not been modified in any way I enclosed MD5 checksums for all files in this archive.
They can be checked with


   md5sum -vc YGM.md5


The 'md5sum' program can normally be found in PGP releases.
The file 'YGM.md5' is also signed with my PGP key to prove that it's untouched.
It can be checked with


   pgp YGM.md5


You can find my public key at @{fg highlight}http://www.sfxsoft.de@{fg text}.


If you don't trust this file, or the MD5 checksums or have problems getting my public key, drop me an email and I'll send you the files.
If you don't trust me, well, I'm afraid I can't help you on this.  In this case you better shouldn't use this program ;-) 



@endnode

@node "xmpl" "Examples"
@{u}@{fg highlight}Examples@{fg text}@{uu}

@{b}1. YGM USER=JohnDoe PASS=secretword SERVER=my.server.com
       CX_POPKEY="LShift Alt F3"@{ub} 

YGM will start up and open the YGM GUI.
If you select 'Connect' it will log into JohnDoe's mailbox at the POP3 server my.server.com at the default port using secretword as password.
Selecting 'Quit' will exit YGM.
If you hide the GUI you can reopen it by pressing the left shift key together with the alt and F3 keys. 


@{b}2. YGM USER=JohnDoe PASS=secretword SERVER=my.server.com:123
       AUTOSTART REPEAT=10 DELAY=0@{ub} 

YGM will start up and open the YGM GUI.
It will immediately log into JohnDoe's mailbox at the POP3 server my.server.com on port number 123 using secretword as password and it will repeat this procedure every 10 minutes.
All status messages in the requester will be updated with no delay. 


@{b}3. YGM ACCESSFILE=ygm.dat DISPLAYBEEP PLAYSOUND=NewMail.8svx
       RUNCOMMAND=MyMailer NOREQ@{ub} 

YGM won't open the YGM GUI.
It will immediately try to log into all mailboxes being found in ygm.dat and then exit.
If there is new mail in one of the mailboxes, all screens will be flashed, the soundfile NewMail.8svx will be played and the program MyMailer will be started.
Informative and/or error messages will be printed to the console if the program was started from the CLI. 


@{b}4. YGM USER=JohnDoe PASS=secretword SERVER=my.server.com NOREQ QUIET NOLOG@{ub} 

YGM won't open the YGM GUI.
It will immediately log into JohnDoe's mailbox once at the POP3 server my.server.com at the default port using secretword as password and then exit.
Messages will neither be printed to the console if the program was started from the CLI nor will they be written to the log file T:YGM.log. 

If you want to run YGM from an AmigaDOS script or from an ARexx script you may find the two example scripts @{b}ygm.scr@{ub} and @{b}ygm.arexx@{ub} helpful, which are to be found in the 's' drawer of this release. 



@endnode

